description: Call or Text Pete @ 678 858 5786 on this super cool garage find. Matching numbers L-82 2 Top Corvette Stingray convertible in as found condition. 1 family owned since new.
Equipped with A/C Power brakes, power steering , TH400 auto trans TWO TOPS! optional hard top & original Folding top In good condition.
There were 30464 Vettes total built in 73, only 4943 Drop tops. Of those convertibles only with only 1300 had hardtops.
Out of the entire 1973 corvette production 16% were equipped with the L-82 High performance small block.

1973 was the first year for the L-82 which is a completely different engine than the regular L-48 350, it includes forged crank, pistons &,the big valve heads and hi po hydraulic cam that  mimics the legendary LT-1 for power with better street manors.
So how many 2 top convertibles had this high winding forged small block???
We recommissioned so it runs drives and stops. 2 tops with original convertible in good shape as is interior. Aftermarket sidepipes and Keystone Classics make this a killer period ride.
Restore or leave it alone
Pictures were taken as found, we have the matching Keystone classics on the front. Car is undergoing service as we speak.

description: This Stingray Corvette T-Top in Purple has 355/350+ hp with 4 speed manual transmission. There's nothing like a very loud and fast 1973 corvette hot rod to cruise around in on nice weekends. This one will definitely get you noticed and wake the neighbors!
Other Specs:  13,370 miles on dash, black interior, Hooker header side pipes, power steering, rally wheels, fiberglass front bumper, Hurst shifter, X-A/C, and much more.

We replaced the tie rod ends, idler arm, power steering hoses, spark plugs, fan clutch, oil pressure sending unit, tail shaft seal, rebuilt Holley carburetors, master cylinder, and much more. We changed the oil and filter and checked and lubed the chassis.

This corvette came from the Virginia/Tennessee area. The last owner built the engine with Weiand tunnel ram, 2 Holley carburetors, Accel coil, Accel spark plug wires, Mallory distributor, World Production Angle Plug heads, gear drive, Pro Comp roller rockers, screw in studs, valve guides, radiator, and much more.

1973 marked the end of the chrome bumper corvette era, with rear chrome bumpers going away in 1974 and being replaced by a rubber bumper. The 1973 was a one-year-only body design. GM also did away with the vacuum-operated wiper door this year, in favor of a longer hood to hide the wipers, and replaced the removable back window with a glue-in window.
